rst understand the factors that have contributed to recent price instability. Does it arise primarily from technological or weather-related supply shocks, or from changes in demand like those induced by the growing use of biofuel? Does financial speculation affect food price volatility? The researchers who contributed to The Economics of Food Price Volatility address these and other questions. They examine the forces driving both recent and historical patterns in food price volatility, as well as the effects of various public policies in affecting this volatility. The chapters include studies of the links between food and energy markets, the impact of biofuel policy on the level and variability of food prices, and the effects of weather-related disruptions in supply. The findings shed light on the way price volatility affects the welfare of farmers, traders, and consumers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAgriculturexEconomic aspectsvCongresses. 0aFood pricesvCongresses. 0aFood supplyvCongresses. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  afood price, groceries, instability, inflation, poverty, income, wealth gap, economics, public policy, farming, agriculture, consumers, market forces, production, waste, biofuel, supply shocks, demand, financial speculation, history, energy, weather, global warming, drought, nonfiction, technology, corn, harvest, commodity, environmentalism, rational storage, bubbles, domestic stabilization, insulation, protection, scarcity, hunger, social sciences.1 aAbbott, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlston, Julian M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Kym, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAulerich, Nicole M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/